


To map "Home" to control on my Mac:
hidutil property \
	--matching '{"VendorID":0x29ea,"ProductID":0x102}' \
	--set '{"UserKeyMapping":[{"HIDKeyboardModifierMappingSrc":0x70000004a,"HIDKeyboardModifierMappingDst":0x7000000e3}]}'


To undo all mappings:
hidutil property \
	--matching '{"VendorID":0x29ea,"ProductID":0x102}' \
	--set '{"UserKeyMapping":[]}'


To get the VendorID and ProductID:
hidutil list | grep -i keyboard
VendorID and ProductID are the first two columns.


Re: values in the set:
They're from the USB HID usage tables.  The 0x700000 prefix means "Keyboard/Keypad usage page" (page 0x07), and the last byte is the key code:

  - 0x4a = Home
  - 0xe3 = Left GUI (which macOS interprets as Left Command)

  The full table is in the USB-IF HID Usage Tables spec.  Quick reference for useful codes:

  hidutil list --matching '{"VendorID":0x29ea,"ProductID":0x102}' 2>&1

  Or for a specific key, press it and watch:

  hidutil monitor --matching '{"VendorID":0x29ea,"ProductID":0x102}'

  That prints the usage code of each key as you press it.  Ctrl+C to stop.

